The COVID-19 is so contagious that all nations are on alert. In order to avoid too many people to the hospital caused cross-infection, to ease the pressure on ambulances, London, the United Kingdom proposed a new coronavirus test "home service. ".

According to a report in the British Medical Journal on February 14, in the pilot area of home testing, suspected Cases of NCP are reported to the centre by the local GP, the NHS non-emergency medical help line (NHS111) and the local emergency department.

The testing center then calls the person to make sure they are in good health, can be isolated at home, and can use protective clothing, goggles, and other personal protective equipment.

Experts will visit patients within 24 hours to take samples, train them on personal protective equipment, advise them on self isolation and how to respond in case their health deteriorates. Once the results are known, the test center will immediately inform the person by telephone that if confirmed, the patient will be referred to a hospital.

The idea of door-to-door testing was first suggested by Dr Laurence John, of the Department of Infectious Diseases at Northwick Park Hospital in London. He told the British Medical Journal that on one afternoon, 25 ambulances in London had been sent to be disinfected because of suspected cases of new pneumonia, and were therefore unable to provide their services properly, causing great inconvenience. The whole process can take an ambulance up to eight hours.

In late January, the North West London NHS Trust launched a home testing service, followed by University College London Hospital, St George's University Hospital and three NHS foundation trusts, Gaye and Saint-Thomas. More than 130 patients have been tested in two weeks.

The medical team also hopes to include community and primary care workers in the effort, including training trainee nurses to perform the tests, which are then processed by a higher level team.

Sarah Roggen, an infectious disease specialist at University College London Hospital, says community testing is an efficient and acceptable way to identify infectious respiratory disease, not only by urging patients to isolate themselves, it can also reduce the occupancy rate of hospital beds and relieve the pressure on ambulances.

Ashley Whittington, an infectious disease specialist at Northwick Park Hospital, said the priority for the UK was to train community teams to expand safe modes of home testing and isolation as quickly as possible, it allows physicians to focus more on treating patients, and ambulances to focus on transporting the really sick.

To date, a total of nine new cases of pneumonia have been confirmed in the UK, of which eight have been cured. More than 2,500 people have been tested for the new coronavirus.
